# Temporal forcing and Markov switching

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm
from itertools import groupby

sns.set_style("darkgrid")

polio_incidence = pd.read_csv("tycho_20220110-154709.csv", 
                            low_memory=False,
                            parse_dates=["PeriodEndDate"],
                            index_col=["PeriodEndDate"]).groupby("PeriodEndDate").sum()[["CountValue"]]
polio_incidence = polio_incidence[(polio_incidence.index >= "1945-01-01") & (polio_incidence.index < "1953-12-31")]

g = sns.relplot(
    data=polio_incidence,
    x="doy", y="CountValue", col="year", hue="year",
    kind="line", palette="crest", linewidth=4, zorder=5,
    col_wrap=3, height=2, aspect=1.5, legend=False,
)

for year, ax in g.axes_dict.items():
    
    sns.lineplot(
        data=polio_incidence, x="doy", y="CountValue", units="year",
        estimator=None, color=".7", linewidth=1, ax=ax,
    )

    ax.axvline(245, color="k")
    ax.set_xlim(0, 365)
    ax.set_ylabel("Cases per week")
    ax.set_xlabel("Day")


g.set_titles("{col_name}")

plt.savefig("polio_temporal_forcing.pdf")

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    plt.axvspan(xmin=boundary[0], xmax=boundary[1], color="#a05195", alpha=0.2)

for i in polio_incidence.year:
    data = polio_incidence[polio_incidence["year"] == i]
    plt.axvline(pd.Series(data[data.doy > 240].first_valid_index()).unique(), color="k", alpha=0.005)

plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Cases/week")
plt.ylim(0, 5250)

plt.savefig("markov_switching_boundaries.pdf")
